{"query": "How does rotational burning compare to leaving unburned patches during prescribed fires for butterfly populations in US prairies?", "summary": "Studies in US prairies show distinct benefits of both rotational burning and leaving unburned patches for butterfly populations. For leaving unburned areas during prescribed burning, one replicated study reported that Karner blue butterfly abundance increased over 2-3 years in oak savannas and prairies where unburned patches were left, and Karner blue butterflies were recorded using all 11 unburned patches surveyed (Action 3879). Additionally, one study found that six out of nine specialist butterfly species were more abundant in pine barrens and prairies where unburned areas were left compared to sites without unburned areas (Action 3879).

For rotational burning, multiple studies show that the total abundance of prairie specialist, grassland and all butterflies was higher on prairies burned more than one, two or four years ago than on prairies burned in the last one or two years under rotational burning management (Action 3883). Two studies found that species richness of butterflies was higher on prairies burned more than one or four years ago than on prairies burned in the last one or two years under rotational burning management (Action 3883). The abundance of grassland and generalist butterflies was highest in the third year after burning, and migrant butterflies in the first year after burning under rotational management (Action 3883).

However, rotational burning showed mixed effects for different species. Four of six studies found that rotational burning in prairies had mixed effects on butterflies compared to unmanaged sites, and one study found that prairies managed by rotational burning had more strongly declining populations of grass-skipper butterflies than unmanaged areas (Action 3883). For fritillary species, rotational burning had variable effects, with some species showing lower abundance in rotationally burned prairies in at least one surveyed region (Action 3883). Importantly, Karner blue butterfly abundance was similar in rotationally burned and unmanaged oak savannas and prairies (Action 3883).", "action_ids": ["3879","3883"]}

